-%% ============================================================
-%% ABSTRACT
-%% ============================================================
-\begin{abstract}
-Multi-agent architectures that decompose tasks across specialized roles are now prevalent in coding tools, scientific workflows, and task automation, yet these systems universally assign roles through system prompts that agents can ignore.
-No existing benchmark structurally enforces role separation or provides ablation controls to measure whether coordination genuinely helps.
-We introduce \textsc{TeamBench}, a benchmark of 811 unique tasks (2{,}434 seeded instances) spanning 25 categories where three roles (Planner, Executor, Verifier) are isolated through Docker container bind mounts that physically enforce access restrictions.
-Across 4{,}200+ runs with 18 models from five provider families, \textbf{the aggregate team benefit is not statistically significant} ($+1.7$\%, $p=0.20$): multi-agent coordination does not uniformly improve performance.
-However, this null aggregate masks a strongly conditional signal.
-On the hardest task quintile, team uplift reaches $+15.3$\% ($p < 0.001$), and team benefit correlates inversely with single-agent capability ($r = -0.35$, $p < 0.001$)---an \emph{Equalizer Effect} whereby structured coordination disproportionately aids weaker models and harder problems.
-Planning adds $+4.8$\% ($p=0.02$), while verification is net-negative, actively hurting 31\% of tasks.
-Cross-model validation confirms that seven of eight closed-source models show positive team uplift, with the weakest benefiting most ($+16.8$\%); a second full ablation on GPT-5-Mini replicates these findings (20\% team vs.\ 2\% oracle).
-All tasks use parameterized generators for contamination resistance.
-TeamBench provides the first empirical characterization of \emph{when} multi-agent teams help, offering actionable deployment guidance on where coordination is cost-effective and where it introduces pure overhead.
-\end{abstract}
-
-%% ============================================================
-%% 1. INTRODUCTION
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Introduction}
-\label{sec:intro}
-
-LLM agents have advanced from code completion to autonomous software engineering~\citep{chen2021codex, jimenez2024swebench, yang2024sweagent}.
-Commercial coding tools such as Claude Code, Codex CLI, and Cursor now operate as single agents with rich tool access, while multi-agent frameworks~\citep{hong2024metagpt, wu2023autogen, qian2024chatdev} decompose tasks across specialized roles: planners that read specifications, executors that write code, and reviewers that validate output.
-This pattern extends beyond software engineering: multi-agent coordination is adopted in scientific research~\citep{park2023generative}, strategic reasoning~\citep{du2024debate}, and complex task automation~\citep{li2023camel}.
-Prior work by the authors~\citep{kim2024agentcoordination} shows that agent architecture and coordination mechanisms significantly affect performance, yet a fundamental question remains unanswered: \emph{when does multi-agent collaboration actually help, and when does coordination overhead outweigh the benefits?}
-
-Existing benchmarks are not designed to answer this question.
-Single-agent benchmarks~\citep{jimenez2024swebench, liu2024agentbench, chan2024mlebench} measure individual capabilities but provide no mechanism for evaluating collaboration.
-Multi-agent frameworks assign roles through system prompts, a design we term \emph{prompt-based honor systems}: a ``Planner'' agent retains full technical capability regardless of its role prompt and can simply ignore its instructions, collapsing the multi-agent system into a single agent with overhead~\citep{hong2024metagpt, qian2024chatdev}.
-Without structural enforcement, observed performance differences cannot be attributed to genuine collaboration versus varying degrees of model compliance.
-Rigorous evaluation requires three properties no existing benchmark provides simultaneously: \textbf{structural enforcement} of role boundaries by the execution environment rather than prompts; \textbf{ablation controls} that systematically degrade team structure to isolate each role's marginal contribution; and \textbf{contamination resistance} through parameterized task generation to prevent memorization.
-
-\textsc{TeamBench} addresses all three requirements.
-We design 811 unique tasks (2{,}434 seeded instances) spanning 25 categories, from security vulnerability patching and distributed systems debugging to adversarial specification traps and cross-codebase integration.
-Roles are enforced through \textbf{Docker container bind mounts}: each agent runs in an isolated container with strictly scoped filesystem access (Table~\ref{tab:roles}).
-No single container can read the full specification, write to the workspace, \emph{and} produce the verification attestation; genuine coordination is therefore structurally required.
-We evaluate performance under \textbf{five ablation conditions} (Table~\ref{tab:conditions}) that systematically remove team components, enabling precise measurement of each role's contribution.
-Every task includes a \textbf{parameterized generator} that produces distinct instances from different random seeds, preventing memorization while ensuring reproducibility across evaluations.
-
-Our central finding is negative at aggregate but strongly positive conditionally---and we argue this is \emph{more} valuable than a blanket positive result.
-Across 4{,}200+ runs with 18 models from five provider families, the aggregate team benefit is not statistically significant ($+1.7$\%, $p=0.20$).
-Multi-agent coordination does not uniformly improve performance, correcting an implicit assumption in much of the multi-agent literature.
-However, the null aggregate conceals a sharply conditional signal: on the hardest task quintile, team uplift reaches $+15.3$\% ($p < 0.001$), and team benefit correlates inversely with single-agent capability ($r = -0.35$, $p < 0.001$).
-We term this the \emph{Equalizer Effect}: structured teamwork disproportionately helps where help is most needed---on difficult problems and with weaker models---while adding pure overhead on tasks that a single capable agent can already solve.
-This finding transforms the question from ``do teams help?'' to ``when do teams help?'', providing the first empirical basis for deciding when multi-agent coordination is cost-effective.
-
-The Equalizer Effect suggests a practical scaling principle: as models improve, the set of tasks where teams outperform solo agents shrinks, but the marginal benefit on the remaining hard frontier intensifies.
-Across eight closed-source models from three provider families, seven show positive team uplift, with the weakest model benefiting most ($+16.8$\%).
-A second full ablation on GPT-5-Mini (250 runs across 50 tasks) replicates the reference findings---full team achieves 20\% pass rate versus 2\% oracle---confirming that these patterns are not model-specific.
-We emphasize that TeamBench is \emph{evaluation infrastructure}, not a deployment prescription: the ablation conditions function as an analytical instrument to decompose \emph{where} collaboration adds value and where it introduces overhead.
-
-In summary, we make the following contributions:
-
-\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,nosep]
-    \item \textbf{First empirical characterization of when multi-agent teams help.} Through 4{,}200+ runs across 18 models and five provider families, we show that aggregate team benefit is not significant ($+1.7$\%, $p=0.20$), but this null masks a strongly conditional signal: planning adds $+4.8$\% ($p = 0.02$) while verification adds no net value; team benefit concentrates on the hardest tasks ($+15.3$\%, $p < 0.001$) and inversely correlates with single-agent capability ($r = -0.35$, $p < 0.001$); weaker models benefit disproportionately from team structure; and seven tasks consistently benefit across all evaluated models while zero tasks consistently suffer.
-    \item \textbf{Benchmark with structural enforcement and contamination resistance.} \textsc{TeamBench} is the first multi-agent benchmark where role separation is enforced by the execution environment (Docker bind mounts), not by prompt compliance. It comprises 811 unique tasks (650 real-world GitHub, 150 ML, 147 DS, and 161+ original categories) across 25 categories at four difficulty levels, including 147 reference-evaluated tasks with complete 5-condition ablation; all 1{,}452 parameterized generators produce deterministic but distinct instances from different random seeds, preventing memorization while enabling reproducible evaluation and holdout leaderboard seeds.
-    \item \textbf{Ablation methodology and metric.} Five ablation conditions systematically vary team structure, enabling isolation of each role's marginal contribution. The Teamwork Necessity Index (TNI) quantifies how much of the oracle-vs-restricted gap the team recovers, with decomposed measures of planning value and verification value.
-\end{enumerate}
