-%% 2. RELATED WORK
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Related Work}
-\label{sec:related}
-
-\paragraph{Agent Benchmarks.}
-HumanEval~\citep{chen2021codex}, MBPP~\citep{austin2021program}, SWE-Bench~\citep{jimenez2024swebench}, TerminalBench~\citep{terminalbench2025}, MLE-Bench~\citep{chan2024mlebench}, and DevBench~\citep{li2024devbench} drive progress on single-agent capabilities; SWE-agent~\citep{yang2024sweagent} and OpenHands~\citep{wang2024opendevin} provide agentic scaffolding.
-SWE-Bench evaluates patch generation for real GitHub issues requiring cross-file reasoning; TerminalBench targets system administration and ML workflow tasks in terminal environments; MLE-Bench assesses machine learning engineering competitions end-to-end.
-GAIA~\citep{mialon2023gaia} tests general AI assistants on multi-step reasoning tasks requiring tool use and web search, while DevBench measures the full software development lifecycle from requirements to tested code.
-None provide controlled ablation conditions for measuring multi-agent teamwork.
-LiveCodeBench~\citep{jain2024livecodebench} addresses contamination via temporal holdouts; TeamBench uses parameterized generators instead, enabling arbitrary holdout seeds without temporal dependence.
-
-\paragraph{Multi-Agent Frameworks.}
-MetaGPT~\citep{hong2024metagpt}, AutoGen~\citep{wu2023autogen}, ChatDev~\citep{qian2024chatdev}, CAMEL~\citep{li2023camel}, multi-agent debate~\citep{du2024debate}, and GPTSwarm~\citep{zhuge2024gptswarm} all enforce roles through prompt instructions.
-MetaGPT coordinates agents through structured message passing with a shared code repository, simulating a software company's division of labor; ChatDev simulates a waterfall development process with communicative agents across design, coding, and testing phases; AutoGen enables flexible multi-agent conversations with customizable interaction patterns and code execution.
-Since a ``Planner'' agent retains full technical capability regardless of its role prompt, it is impossible to isolate whether improvements stem from genuine collaboration or a single dominant agent.
-TeamBench enforces role boundaries at the container level, making role separation a structural property rather than a prompt-compliance assumption.
-ReAct~\citep{yao2023react}, Reflexion~\citep{shinn2024reflexion}, AgentBench~\citep{liu2024agentbench}, GAIA~\citep{mialon2023gaia}, TAU-Bench~\citep{yao2024taubench}, and BrowseComp~\citep{browsecomp2025} advance agent evaluation methodology but do not measure collaboration.
-
-\paragraph{Evaluation Methodology.}
-Evaluation methodology for agent benchmarks requires attention to contamination, statistical validity, and reproducibility.
-AgentBench~\citep{liu2024agentbench} and AgentBoard provide multi-environment evaluation suites spanning web, database, and operating system tasks; GAIA~\citep{mialon2023gaia} tests general AI assistants on multi-step reasoning requiring tool integration; TAU-Bench~\citep{yao2024taubench} measures tool-augmented performance in domain-specific settings such as retail and airline customer service.
-LiveCodeBench~\citep{jain2024livecodebench} uses temporal holdouts to prevent contamination; BIG-Bench~\citep{srivastava2023bigbench} demonstrated the value of comprehensive task diversity across hundreds of skills.
-TeamBench combines parameterized generation (for contamination resistance) with paired bootstrap testing (for statistical rigor) and partial scoring (for fine-grained comparison).
