-%% ============================================================
-%% 3. TEAMBENCH
-%% ============================================================
-\section{TeamBench}
-\label{sec:teambench}
-
-\subsection{Role Separation via Container Isolation}
-\label{sec:roles}
-
-TeamBench enforces role boundaries through \textbf{Docker container bind mounts}: each of the three roles runs in an isolated container with a strictly scoped filesystem view enforced by Linux permissions.
-Table~\ref{tab:roles} summarizes the access matrix, creating deliberate \emph{information asymmetry}: the Planner reads \texttt{spec.md} but cannot execute code; the Executor modifies the workspace but never sees the full specification; the Verifier checks compliance and writes \texttt{attestation.json} (a missing attestation is an automatic failure).
-No single container can simultaneously access the full specification, modify the workspace, and attest to correctness, so genuine coordination is structurally required.
-
-\paragraph{Three-role decomposition.}
-The Planner--Executor--Verifier decomposition represents one natural factorization that separates \emph{understanding} (reading and decomposing the specification), \emph{implementation} (modifying code and running commands), and \emph{validation} (checking compliance against requirements).
-Merging any two roles collapses a structurally distinct capability: removing the Verifier yields a two-role team that cannot independently validate, while removing the Planner yields one that cannot relay specification knowledge.
-Both merges are tested as ablation conditions (Table~\ref{tab:conditions}), confirming that the three-role decomposition is principled rather than arbitrary.
-Alternative decompositions (e.g., two-role Spec-Reader + Implementer, or four-role Architect + Coder + Tester + Reviewer) are valid and may yield different findings; we leave their evaluation to future work.
-
-\paragraph{Container-level enforcement.}
-Prompt-based role assignment creates an observational study: observed compliance may reflect model obedience rather than structural necessity, and non-compliance is undetectable.
-Container bind mounts create a \emph{controlled experiment} in which role boundaries are physically enforced by the operating system.
-This distinction is critical: without structural enforcement, one cannot attribute performance differences to the team structure itself versus varying degrees of model compliance with role instructions.
-
