-\subsection{Task Design}
-\label{sec:tasks}
-
-TeamBench comprises 811 unique tasks (2{,}434 seeded instances) spanning 25 categories (full distribution in Table~\ref{tab:distribution}, Appendix~\ref{app:task-distribution}).
-Tasks cover security vulnerability patching, data pipeline repair, incident root-cause analysis, distributed systems debugging, cryptographic correctness verification, and adversarial specification traps.
-The benchmark is deliberately weighted toward hard and expert tasks (80\%) where multi-agent collaboration is most likely to provide value.
-
-\paragraph{Task archetypes.}
-Tasks fall into five archetypes that test distinct collaboration modes.
-\emph{Relay} tasks require the Planner to transmit critical specification details that the Executor cannot independently access (e.g., which bugs are intentional).
-\emph{Open-ended} tasks admit multiple valid approaches and are graded by rubric, testing whether planning narrows the solution space productively (10 tasks).
-\emph{Adversarial} tasks embed plausible but incorrect information in the workspace, requiring the Planner to warn the Executor about traps (8 TRAP tasks plus 10 real-incident tasks sourced from CVEs and post-mortems).
-\emph{Discovery} tasks hide data quality issues that the Executor must find through exploration, with the specification describing what to look for but not where (6 tasks).
-\emph{Synthesis} tasks require correlating evidence across multiple documents, testing whether the Planner can distill cross-document signals into actionable guidance (6 tasks).
-
-\paragraph{Originally authored tasks.}
-Information asymmetry must be designed into the task by construction.
-In benchmarks derived from real GitHub issues (e.g., SWE-bench), the issue description typically contains enough information for any single agent to proceed; there is no structural reason why a Planner must relay knowledge the Executor cannot independently access.
-Our tasks separate specification from workspace \emph{by design}: the specification contains critical details (which bugs are intentional, which constraints are hidden, which edge cases must be handled) that are deliberately absent from the workspace and the brief.
-This guarantees that the Planner's relay is not redundant, enabling a meaningful test of whether team coordination adds value beyond what a single agent with full access achieves.
-
-The benchmark remains far from saturated: the strongest closed-source model achieves only 42.9\% pass@1 under the best condition.
-Reliability analysis shows team coordination scales dramatically with retries: GPT-5.4 achieves 42.9\% pass@1, 82.9\% pass@3, and 95.6\% pass@5 under Full Team, versus 0\% pass@1 and 0\% pass@3 under Oracle---the team structure converts zero-pass tasks into high-reliability successes.
-The parameterized generators ensure that memorization cannot substitute for genuine problem-solving.
-
-\paragraph{Real-Data Anchoring.}
-To ensure ecological validity, 30 tasks use canonical public datasets---UCI Adult Income~\citep{dua2019uci}, Ames Housing, NYC Taxi, FRED economic time series, WHO Global Health Observatory, and others---as their foundation, replacing synthetic data-generating processes with authentic data distributions that the data science community already trusts.
-Each task is parameterized through subsampling, feature selection, and methodological flaw injection, maintaining contamination resistance while grounding evaluation in real-world data patterns.
-These real-data tasks span four collaboration archetypes beyond information relay: \emph{open-ended design} (10~tasks with multiple valid analytical approaches, graded by rubric), \emph{adversarial workspace} (8~tasks containing plausible but flawed analyses), \emph{executor-discovery} (6~tasks with hidden data quality issues), and \emph{multi-source synthesis} (6~tasks requiring cross-document evidence correlation).
-An additional 10 real-incident tasks (RINC) are sourced from published CVEs and post-mortem reports, grounding incident-response evaluation in documented production failures rather than synthetic scenarios.
-
-Each task includes: (1) a specification (\texttt{spec.md}) with all requirements and edge cases; (2) a brief (\texttt{brief.md}) providing a concise executor-facing summary; (3) a workspace with initial code (typically buggy or incomplete); (4) a setup script; and (5) a deterministic grader (\texttt{grade.sh}) producing a partial score in $[0, 1]$.
-Eleven tasks (GH1 to GH11) are sourced from closed GitHub issues in Flask, Click, httpx, Requests, Pydantic, Django, pytest, FastAPI, SQLAlchemy, Celery, and Werkzeug; the specification contains the full issue discussion (Planner-only) while the brief describes only the user-facing symptom.
-A 28-task \textbf{TeamBench-Mini} subset is used for cross-model comparison (Appendix~\ref{app:task-construction}).
-Full construction details, the task distribution table, and the TeamBench-Mini subset definition are in Appendix~\ref{app:task-construction}.
-
-\subsection{Parameterized Generators for Contamination Resistance}
-\label{sec:generators}
-
-Every task has a Python generator that produces deterministic but distinct workspace files from different random seeds.
-The generators produce 2{,}434 seeded instances across seeds $\{0, 1, 2\}$; arbitrary additional seeds enable holdout leaderboard evaluation.
-Generators vary task-relevant parameters (config values, API field names, bug locations) while preserving structural complexity, protecting against value memorization.
-
-\subsection{Ablation Conditions and the Teamwork Necessity Index}
-\label{sec:tni}
-
-We evaluate each task under five conditions (Table~\ref{tab:conditions}) that systematically vary team structure:
-
