-\begin{tabular}{llccc}
-\toprule
-Condition & Description & Plan & Execute & Verify \\
-\midrule
-Oracle & Single agent, full tool access & \multicolumn{3}{c}{(unrestricted)} \\
-Restricted & Single agent, executor-only tools & -- & \checkmark & -- \\
-Full Team & Three-role team & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark \\
-Team, No Plan & Two-role team (skip planning) & -- & \checkmark & \checkmark \\
-Team, No Verify & Two-role team (skip verification) & \checkmark & \checkmark & -- \\
-\bottomrule
-\end{tabular}
-\end{table}
-
-Oracle (full access) and Restricted (executor-only, no spec) bracket single-agent performance; the three team conditions isolate each role's contribution.
-The \textbf{Teamwork Necessity Index} (TNI) measures how much of the oracle-vs-restricted performance gap the team recovers:
-\begin{equation}
-\text{TNI} = \frac{S_{\text{team}} - S_{\text{restricted}}}{\max(\epsilon,\; S_{\text{oracle}} - S_{\text{restricted}})}
-\label{eq:tni}
-\end{equation}
-where $\epsilon = 0.05$ prevents instability when full access provides little benefit. TNI $= 1.0$ means the team fully recovers single-agent advantage; TNI $> 1.0$ means the team exceeds the oracle ceiling.
-We also report Planning Value $= S_{\text{full}} - S_{\text{no\_plan}}$ and Verification Value $= S_{\text{full}} - S_{\text{no\_verify}}$, and classify tasks as HIGH-TNI, TEAM-HELPS, NEUTRAL, or TEAM-HURTS based on the neutrality threshold $\pm 0.05$.
-Throughout this paper, \emph{team uplift} refers to the difference $S_{\text{full}} - S_{\text{oracle}}$ in partial scores unless otherwise noted.
-We note that TNI becomes unstable when the necessity gap $S_{\text{oracle}} - S_{\text{restricted}}$ is near zero (both conditions score similarly), because small score fluctuations produce large TNI swings; the $\epsilon$ floor mitigates but does not eliminate this sensitivity.
-We therefore report TNI only for the 38 tasks with necessity gaps exceeding 0.05 and supplement it with direct score comparisons throughout.
-Given that TNI is undefined for 74\% of tasks (those with necessity gaps below $\varepsilon$), we treat it as a supplementary metric and rely primarily on direct score comparisons (planning value, verification value, and absolute uplift) throughout the paper.
-
-%% ============================================================
-%% 4. EXPERIMENT
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Experiment}
-\label{sec:experiment}
-
-We conduct two complementary evaluations.
-The \textbf{reference evaluation} uses Gemini 3 Flash Preview as the primary model, evaluating all 147 tasks with complete data under five ablation conditions with seed 0, plus seeds 1 and 2 for a 39-task multi-seed subset, yielding 1{,}417 reference model runs.
-We select Gemini 3 Flash because it offers broad API availability and consistent throughput across all conditions.
-
-The \textbf{cross-model evaluation} covers the 28-task TeamBench-Mini subset under all five conditions with eight closed-source models from three provider families: Gemini 3 Flash Preview and Gemini 3.1 Flash Lite Preview (Google), GPT-5.4, GPT-5.3-chat, GPT-5-Mini, and GPT-5-Nano (OpenAI), and Claude Sonnet 4.6 and Claude Haiku 4.5 (Anthropic), plus six open-source models (Qwen2.5-Coder-32B, Qwen3-4B/8B/14B, DeepSeek-R1-Distill-32B, Gemma~3~27B).
-We additionally evaluate seven open-source models (Qwen3 4B through 32B, Qwen3-Coder-30B, DeepSeek-R1-Distill-32B) served via vLLM.
-Combined with 55 GitHub task runs, 84 topology ablation runs, and a second full ablation on GPT-5-Mini (250 runs), the benchmark includes 4{,}200+ evaluated runs across 18 models.
-
-Each agent role is implemented as a tool-calling loop with configurable step limits: the Planner receives up to 15 steps, the Executor up to 25, and the Verifier up to 10.
-All runs use Docker containers on 32-vCPU, 64~GB nodes with temperature 0.0 and 4{,}096 maximum tokens per step.
-Statistical significance is assessed via paired bootstrap tests with 10{,}000 iterations over task-level score differences.
-All tasks are graded by deterministic shell scripts that produce partial scores in $[0, 1]$.
