-\label{tab:main-results}
-\small
-\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
-\toprule
-Metric & Oracle & Restricted & Full & No Plan & No Verify \\
-\midrule
-Avg.\ Score & 0.575 & 0.571 & \textbf{0.592} & 0.544 & \textbf{0.592} \\
-\bottomrule
-\end{tabular}
-\end{table}
-
-Of the 147 tasks with complete five-condition ablation data, 63 (42.9\%) show $S_{\text{full}} > S_{\text{oracle}}$; applying a neutrality threshold of $|S_{\text{full}} - S_{\text{oracle}}| \leq 0.05$ yields the classification: HIGH-TNI (51), TEAM-HELPS (4), NEUTRAL (60), and TEAM-HURTS (32).
-Thus, 55 tasks (37.4\%) show team improvement exceeding the neutrality threshold.
-Among the 38 tasks with necessity gaps exceeding 0.05, the average TNI is \textbf{0.664}, indicating that teamwork recovers approximately two-thirds of the gap between the restricted and oracle conditions. We emphasize that this average is computed over only 38 of 147 tasks; the direct comparisons reported above are more broadly applicable.
-
-The average planning value across tasks is $+4.8$\% while the average verification value is $+0.0$\%.
-Planning provides consistent value by guiding executors with specification knowledge they cannot independently access, whereas current LLM verifiers often introduce overhead without proportional benefit.
-The Team, No Verify condition (Planner + Executor, no Verifier) achieves the highest average score precisely because it retains the planning benefit while avoiding the verification cost.
-
-We assess statistical significance using paired bootstrap tests (10{,}000 iterations) over the 147 task-level score differences. The aggregate team-to-oracle difference ($+1.7$\%) does not reach significance ($p = 0.20$; 95\% CI: $[-2.3, +5.8]$\%). The only significant pairwise effect is planning: Full outperforms No Plan by $+4.8$\% ($p = 0.02$; CI: $[+0.1, +9.5]$\%). Verification adds no significant value (Full $\approx$ No Verify, $p = 0.50$). We note that the planning significance ($p=0.02$) does not survive Bonferroni correction across the five primary pairwise comparisons ($\alpha_{\text{corrected}} = 0.01$); however, the category-level findings (testing $p=0.001$, GitHub $p < 0.001$, multi-layer $p < 0.001$) and the Q1 quintile finding ($p < 0.001$) remain significant after correction. We report uncorrected $p$-values throughout and flag which findings survive correction. The team benefit is not uniform but concentrates in specific task subsets, motivating the conditional analyses in Sections~\ref{sec:category}--\ref{sec:equalizer}.
-
-To test whether better prompting of the oracle could recover the team benefit without multi-agent decomposition, we evaluate two structured oracle conditions on the 28-task TeamBench-Mini subset: Oracle-CoT (prompted to read the specification, plan, then implement) and Oracle-2Pass (specification reading and implementation in separate passes). Neither improves over the regular oracle: Oracle-CoT scores 0.640 ($-6.4$\% vs.\ oracle 0.704), while Oracle-2Pass scores 0.698 ($-0.6$\%). The full team (0.754, $+5.0$\%) remains the strongest condition. Chain-of-thought prompting actually degrades single-agent performance, likely because the structured planning overhead consumes steps that would otherwise be spent on implementation. This establishes that the team benefit is genuinely structural and cannot be replicated by prompt engineering alone. Full details are in Appendix~\ref{app:enhanced-oracle}.
-
-Figure~\ref{fig:classification} shows the distribution of tasks across the four TNI-based categories.
-These patterns are validated on 11 real-world GitHub bugs where no oracle agent fully passes but teams solve 27\% (Appendix~\ref{app:gh-tasks}).
