-\subsection{Per-Category Analysis}
-\label{sec:category}
-
-Three categories reach statistical significance for positive team uplift: testing ($+18.9$\%, $p = 0.001$), real-world GitHub ($+15.8$\%, $p < 0.001$), and multi-layer ($+12.6$\%, $p < 0.001$).
-These categories benefit from a Planner that decomposes specification requirements into actionable steps before execution.
-Two categories show significant negative uplift: cross-system ($-20.0$\%, $p = 0.04$) and pipeline ($-11.2$\%, $p = 0.03$), where tasks are self-contained enough that coordination overhead exceeds benefit.
-The remaining 14 categories show no significant difference (per-category figures in Appendix~\ref{app:category-figure}).
-
-\subsection{Task Difficulty and Team Benefit}
-\label{sec:equalizer}
-
-The single strongest predictor of team uplift is the oracle score itself: how well a single unconstrained agent performs ($r = -0.348$, $p < 0.001$, $n = 147$).
-
-Table~\ref{tab:equalizer} presents team uplift stratified by oracle performance quintiles.
-Tasks where the oracle scores below 22\% show an average team uplift of \textbf{+15.3\%} (bootstrap 95\% CI: $[+6.4, +26.1]$, $p < 0.05$), while tasks where the oracle exceeds 90\% show a \emph{negative} average uplift of $-$7.4\%.
-This \textbf{equalizer effect} (team coordination disproportionately benefits tasks that are hardest for individual agents) is the strongest empirical pattern in our data and complements the cross-model finding (Section~\ref{sec:crossmodel}) that weaker models benefit from teamwork on more tasks.
-Mechanistic analysis reveals that the equalizer effect is better characterized as a \emph{capability sweet-spot}: team benefit follows an inverted-U with model capability, peaking at mid-tier oracle scores (0.40 to 0.70). Contrary to the initial framing, very weak models (oracle $< 0.30$) are actively harmed by team overhead because they cannot execute even well-structured plans, while very strong models (oracle $> 0.80$) see only marginal gains because they already succeed without coordination. The benefit concentrates where models are capable enough to follow plans but not capable enough to self-organize. Specifically, spec relay is not the primary mechanism: tasks where specification access matters most (high necessity gap) actually benefit \emph{least} from teams ($r = -0.446$, $p < 0.001$). Step-limit exhaustion and implicit chain-of-thought are similarly unsupported (Appendix~\ref{app:equalizer-mechanism}).
-
