-Both extremes are statistically significant: Q1 team uplift ($+15.3$\%, $p < 0.001$) and Q5 team deficit ($-7.0$\%, $p = 0.04$). The Q1 to Q5 difference of $22.3$\% confirms that the equalizer effect is not an artifact of aggregation but a genuine interaction between task difficulty and team benefit.
-
-The implication is actionable: \emph{deploy multi-agent teams on your hardest tasks, not your easiest}.
-When a single agent already achieves $>$80\% on a task, adding team coordination is more likely to introduce overhead than improvement.
-When a single agent scores below 30\%, the Planner's specification relay and structured decomposition consistently rescue performance: the team converts 12\% average oracle score into 27\% average full-team score, more than doubling the partial score.
-
-Easy tasks show high uplift not because they are inherently simple, but because their oracle scores tend to be low (mean 0.485), placing them in the regime where team coordination has the highest marginal value.
-Author-assigned difficulty labels ($r = -0.111$, $p = 0.18$) are a poor predictor of team benefit; empirical oracle performance is far more informative.
-
-\subsection{Planning vs.\ Verification}
-\label{sec:components}
-
-Figure~\ref{fig:components} plots planning value against verification value for each task that has both team conditions evaluated.
-The dominant pattern is positive planning value combined with near-zero or negative verification value: 44\% of tasks benefit from planning, while only 27\% benefit from verification (40/147) and 31\% are actively hurt (45/147).
-The maximum planning value is +100\% (INC2\_data\_corruption, where the Planner identified the correct corruption source from the specification, enabling a targeted fix).
-The most common failure mode for verification is false rejection: the Verifier incorrectly classifies a correct solution as incomplete and triggers unnecessary rework.
-
