-\subsection{Empirical Difficulty Recalibration}
-\label{sec:difficulty-recalibration}
-
-Author-assigned difficulty labels are essentially uncorrelated with empirical task difficulty (Spearman $\rho = 0.010$, $p = 0.91$, $n = 151$; Table~\ref{tab:difficulty_calibration}), where empirical difficulty is defined as $1 - \bar{s}_{\text{oracle}}$ averaged across all models and seeds.
-Only 25\% of tasks retain their original difficulty label after recalibration using empirical thresholds.
-This finding strengthens the Equalizer Effect (Section~\ref{sec:equalizer}): the correlation between oracle performance and team uplift ($r = -0.348$) is driven by task-intrinsic properties rather than author label artifacts.
-When stratifying by empirical difficulty quintiles instead of author labels, the Equalizer Effect becomes even more pronounced ($\rho = 0.243$, $p = 0.0008$), confirming that team benefit concentrates on genuinely hard tasks regardless of how they were originally labeled.
