-%% 6. DISCUSSION
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Discussion}
-\label{sec:discussion}
-
-\subsection{Conditions for Team Benefit}
-\label{sec:when-helps}
-
-The equalizer effect (Section~\ref{sec:equalizer}) provides the broadest answer: team coordination helps most when single agents fail.
-Three task characteristics predict positive team uplift.
-\textbf{Information asymmetry}: when the specification contains critical details not in the brief (e.g., which bugs are intentional design choices), the Planner's relay is essential.
-\textbf{Structured decomposition}: tasks requiring staged execution benefit from upfront planning; in LH2\_budgeted\_workflow the team achieves 0.83 versus 0.04 for the oracle.
-\textbf{Multi-criterion verification}: verification helps on 27\% of tasks (primarily adversarial traps) but hurts on 31\% (Section~\ref{sec:components}).
-
-Team overhead is most damaging in two scenarios.
-\textbf{Self-contained tasks}: when a single agent needs no additional specification knowledge, coordination overhead reduces performance.
-\textbf{Verifier hallucination}: the Verifier incorrectly rejects valid solutions on 31\% of tasks, triggering rework loops.
-Figure~\ref{fig:oracle-vs-team} shows that team wins concentrate among harder tasks.
-Three directions for improving verification: tool-augmented verification (EA results show TNI $> 1.0$ when roles have specialized tools), confidence-calibrated rejection, and selective deployment on adversarial tasks.
-
-\subsection{Tool Specialization}
-\label{sec:ea}
-
-On five Expertise Asymmetry (EA) tasks where the Planner has static analysis tools (Bandit, Mypy, Ruff) and the Verifier can run test suites, the team achieves 72\% versus 32\% oracle (TNI = 1.25), \emph{exceeding} the theoretical oracle ceiling.
-This points to a design principle: teams should be structured around tool specialization, not just information separation.
-Detailed results are in Appendix~\ref{app:ea-results}.
-
-\subsection{Design Implications}
-\label{sec:implications}
-
-The following implications are specific to the Planner-Executor-Verifier decomposition evaluated in this paper; alternative role structures may produce different patterns.
-
-TeamBench serves as evaluation infrastructure: the ablation conditions reveal which capabilities (planning, execution, verification) are bottlenecks for current models, rather than prescribing the three-role pipeline as a deployment architecture.
-A topology ablation over four alternative coordination patterns confirms the standard pipeline as optimal (Appendix~\ref{app:topology}).
-
-\textbf{Deploy teams selectively.} Use multi-agent coordination when a single agent scores below ${\sim}50\%$; above this threshold coordination overhead is more likely to hurt.
-Concretely: (1) below 30\% oracle, deploy the full three-phase team (+15\% expected uplift); (2) 30\% to 80\%, deploy Planner + Executor only; (3) above 80\%, use the single agent directly.
-For adversarial or trap-prone tasks, add a Verifier regardless of oracle performance.
-
-\textbf{Verify-First as an alternative.} Using verification as upfront gap analysis rather than post-hoc judgment avoids the rework loops that cause 30\% of verification harm.
-
-\textbf{Scaling.} Team benefit is driven by information distribution, not capability amplification. As long as complex software requires understanding distributed across multiple documents, structured coordination will persist in value even as individual capabilities improve.
-
-Figure~\ref{fig:oracle-vs-team} (Appendix~\ref{app:oracle-vs-team-figure}) visualizes the per-task oracle-vs-team scatter.
-
-%% ============================================================
-%% 7. LIMITATIONS
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Limitations}
-\label{sec:limitations}
-
-\paragraph{Evaluation scope.}
-The primary evaluation uses a single reference model (Gemini 3 Flash Preview).
-Cross-model validation on 28 tasks with 18 models from five provider families mitigates model-specific bias. A second full ablation on GPT-5-Mini (250 runs across 50 tasks) replicates the reference findings, with full team achieving 20\% pass rate versus 2\% oracle.
-A partial ablation on GPT-5-Nano (131 runs) further confirms the Equalizer Effect: oracle achieves 8\% while team reaches 19\%, with the weakest model again showing the largest relative gain.
-Open-source models achieve near-zero pass rates due to tool-use infrastructure failures (malformed calls, context overflow), not capability limitations (Appendix~\ref{app:open-source}), limiting the generalizability of findings to that model class.
-
-\paragraph{Team structure.}
-All experiments use a fixed three-role pipeline with single-turn, file-based communication.
-Real software teams engage in multi-round dialogue, dynamic role assignment, and iterative refinement.
-The topology ablation (Appendix~\ref{app:topology}) explores four alternatives but all share the single-pass constraint.
-Heterogeneous teams (different models per role) remain untested with models of sufficiently different capability, and learned routing policies that adaptively select team configurations are beyond the current scope.
-
-\paragraph{Task scope and oracle baseline.}
-All 811 tasks are software engineering tasks with deterministic grading.
-Findings may not generalize to domains with subjective correctness (design, creative writing) or ambiguous information (medical diagnosis).
-We tested two enhanced oracle baselines (Oracle-CoT and Oracle-2Pass) that add structured planning to the single-agent prompt (Appendix~\ref{app:enhanced-oracle}). Neither improves over the standard oracle, establishing that the team benefit is not recoverable by prompt engineering. However, we tested only one model; enhanced prompting strategies may interact differently with other architectures.
-
-\paragraph{Adoption and accessibility.}
-To lower the barrier to adoption, we provide framework adapters for AutoGen, CrewAI, and LangGraph, enabling teams to plug TeamBench tasks into existing multi-agent pipelines without modifying their orchestration logic.
-For open-source models, we have implemented lenient tool-call parsing that tolerates common malformed output patterns (e.g., XML-style tool calls, missing JSON delimiters), partially addressing the tool-use infrastructure failures documented in Appendix~\ref{app:open-source}.
-
-\paragraph{Human baselines.}
-No human team baselines exist for TeamBench; this remains the most significant gap in validation.
-Without them, it is unclear whether the patterns observed (negative verification value, the equalizer effect, planning as the dominant contributor) reflect properties of the tasks themselves or limitations specific to current LLM agents.
-Human teams may exhibit different failure modes (e.g., coordination overhead from communication latency rather than hallucination), and establishing human baselines would clarify which findings are fundamental to the task structure versus artifacts of model behavior.
-
-%% ============================================================
-%% 8. CONCLUSION
-%% ============================================================
-\section{Conclusion}
-\label{sec:conclusion}
-
-TeamBench enforces role separation at the operating system level, enabling controlled measurement of multi-agent collaboration on 811 unique tasks across 25 categories and five provider families.
-Our experiments across 4{,}200+ runs with 18 models reveal that planning is the primary driver of team value ($+4.8$\%, $p=0.02$), while verification as currently implemented by LLMs does not help on average and actively hurts 31\% of tasks.
-Team coordination is most valuable on the hardest tasks ($+15.3$\%, $p < 0.001$) and for the weakest models ($r = -0.35$ between single-agent capability and team benefit), functioning as an equalizer that compensates for individual limitations rather than amplifying already-strong capabilities.
-Cross-model validation across all six closed-source models confirms this pattern: every model shows positive team uplift, with the weakest model benefiting most ($+32.1$\%), and zero tasks consistently suffer from team structure across all models.
-These findings suggest that the multi-agent community should invest in better planning architectures, including structured specification decomposition, tool-augmented analysis, and selective deployment based on task difficulty, rather than adding more verification stages to existing pipelines.
-The benchmark's conditional findings (team benefit depends on task difficulty, category, and model capability) provide a foundation for developing adaptive scaffolding that deploys coordination selectively: full teams on the hardest tasks, planning-only for moderate difficulty, and single agents where they already succeed.
-As models improve, TeamBench's parameterized generators and difficulty spectrum will continue to differentiate model families on their collaborative capabilities.
-
