-\section{Task Construction Process}
-\label{app:task-construction}
-
-Each task was manually designed through a three-stage pipeline. In the \emph{design} stage, the author wrote the specification (\texttt{spec.md}), brief (\texttt{brief.md}), and workspace files, ensuring that the specification contains critical information absent from the workspace to create genuine information asymmetry. In the \emph{validation} stage, the grading script (\texttt{grade.sh}) was developed and tested against both correct and incorrect solutions to verify discriminative power. In the \emph{pilot evaluation} stage, the task was run under all five ablation conditions with the reference model to confirm that (a) the oracle can achieve a non-trivial score, (b) the grader produces meaningful partial scores, and (c) the task exercises the intended teamwork dynamics. Parameterized generators were then written to produce seed-dependent variants; each generator randomizes surface parameters (variable names, configuration values, bug locations, file structures) while preserving the structural complexity and information asymmetry properties validated in piloting. The 11 GitHub-sourced tasks (GH1--GH11) were adapted from real open-source bug reports and did not go through parameterized generation. The total development effort was approximately 6 person-months across all 164 tasks.
-
-A 28-task \textbf{TeamBench-Mini} subset (balanced across all 19 categories) is used for cross-model comparison and as the recommended entry point for leaderboard submissions.
-
