-\section{Task Example: TRAP5\_security\_theater}
-\label{app:example}
-
-To illustrate the information asymmetry that drives teamwork value, consider TRAP5\_security\_theater.
-The workspace contains a web application and an audit report listing 10 security findings.
-The specification (\texttt{spec.md}), visible only to the Planner and Verifier, reveals that findings 1 through 4 are \emph{intentional false positives}: the auditor misidentified correct security patterns as vulnerabilities.
-Only findings 5 through 10 are genuine.
-
-An oracle agent with full access achieves 0.71 by correctly identifying most false positives.
-A restricted agent (executor-only, no specification access) also scores 0.71 by naively fixing everything, which is accidentally correct on the genuine findings.
-The full team achieves 0.71 to 0.79 depending on how effectively the Planner communicates which findings to skip.
-This task demonstrates that teamwork value depends critically on the quality of inter-agent communication, not just the structural separation of roles.
-
