-
-\paragraph{File access boundaries.}
-Each role has a distinct set of allowed read/write roots enforced via absolute path prefix checks:
-\begin{itemize}[nosep]
-    \item \textbf{Planner}: Can read the full specification (\texttt{spec.md}) and the task directory. Cannot read or write the workspace.
-    \item \textbf{Executor}: Can read the brief (\texttt{brief.md}), workspace, and messages. Can write to the workspace and reports directory. Cannot read the full specification.
-    \item \textbf{Verifier}: Can read the specification, workspace (read-only), and reports. Can write only to the submission directory (attestation). Cannot modify the workspace.
-\end{itemize}
-
-When running in Docker mode, these boundaries are enforced via container bind mounts: each role's container only mounts the directories it is permitted to access, making it impossible to circumvent restrictions even through shell escapes.
