-\section{Core System Prompts}
-\label{app:prompts}
-
-Below are the system prompts used for each role in the standard three-role pipeline.
-
-\promptbox{Planner System Prompt}{You are the Planner. You have access to the full task specification. Your job is to understand the requirements, decompose the goal, and create a clear plan. You CANNOT execute commands or modify the workspace. You MUST communicate your plan to the Executor by calling the \texttt{send\_message} tool. Highlight hidden constraints and edge cases the Executor might miss.}
-
-\promptbox{Executor System Prompt}{You are the Executor. You can run commands and edit files in the workspace. You only have access to a brief summary of the task (not the full spec). Follow the Planner's instructions carefully. For file reads/writes, use paths relative to the workspace (e.g., \texttt{app/main.py}). When done with your work, send a message to the verifier and output DONE. Ask the Planner for clarification if requirements are unclear.}
-
-\promptbox{Verifier System Prompt}{You are the Verifier. You independently verify whether the task was completed correctly. You have read-only access to the workspace and reports. You have access to the full task specification for checking compliance. You CANNOT execute commands or modify the workspace. Your job: check every requirement, identify violations, and produce \texttt{attestation.json}. If requirements are not met, send feedback to the Executor and set \texttt{verdict='fail'}. Only set \texttt{verdict='pass'} when ALL requirements are satisfied. When done, output DONE.}
-
-\promptbox{Oracle System Prompt}{You are a software engineer. You have access to the full task specification and can execute any command. Complete the task to the best of your ability.}
-
-\noindent The oracle has access to all four tools with no restrictions on file paths or command execution. Prompts are intentionally concise; the structural enforcement of tool access (Appendix~\ref{app:tools}) carries most of the role separation burden rather than relying on prompt compliance.
-
-\section{Qualitative Analysis}
-\label{app:qualitative}
-
-We present detailed case studies illustrating when and why teamwork helps or hurts, drawn from representative tasks across the benchmark.
-
-\subsection{When Teamwork Helps: LH2\_budgeted\_workflow}
-
-This long-horizon task requires implementing a multi-step workflow migration under a computational budget constraint.
-The specification describes six migration phases that must be executed in order, with rollback conditions for each phase.
-
-\promptbox{Planner Output (excerpt)}{Phase ordering is critical. Phases 1-3 must complete before Phase 4 begins because Phase 4 reads the output of Phase 3. Budget allocation: 40\% to phases 1-3 (data migration), 35\% to phases 4-5 (validation), 25\% reserve for rollback. Key constraint: Phase 2 output format changed from CSV to JSON in the current version; the executor must update the parser before running Phase 3.}
-
-The oracle agent, despite having full access, attempts all phases simultaneously without budget management and achieves only 0.04. The full team achieves 0.83: the Planner decomposes the specification into ordered phases with budget allocations, enabling the Executor to implement each phase sequentially. This represents a 20$\times$ improvement, demonstrating that planning decomposition is critical for long-horizon tasks where the specification contains implicit ordering constraints.
-
-\subsection{When Teamwork Helps: TRAP5\_security\_theater}
-
-This adversarial task presents 10 audit findings, but the specification reveals that findings 1 through 4 are intentional false positives (the auditor misidentified correct security patterns as vulnerabilities).
-
-The oracle scores 0.71 by correctly identifying most false positives through code analysis alone. The restricted agent also scores 0.71 by naively fixing everything, which accidentally preserves the correct code for genuine findings. The full team achieves 0.71 to 0.79: the Planner reads the specification and communicates which findings to skip, but the effectiveness depends on the clarity of the Planner's message. This highlights that teamwork value depends on \emph{communication quality}, not just structural role separation.
-
-\subsection{When Teamwork Hurts: GO1\_concurrency\_fix}
-
-This task requires fixing a race condition in a Go concurrent server. The bug is localized to a single file, and the fix (adding a mutex) is self-contained.
-
-The oracle scores 0.75 by directly identifying and fixing the race condition. The full team scores 0.00: the Planner, unable to execute code, produces a plan based on the specification that over-complicates the fix by suggesting channel-based synchronization. The Executor follows the Planner's instructions and introduces new bugs. This is the prototypical ``self-contained task'' failure mode: when a single agent can solve the problem without additional specification knowledge, the communication overhead of multi-agent coordination is counterproductive.
-
-\subsection{When Verification Hurts: TEST2\_regression}
-
-The No Verify condition scores 1.00 while the full team scores only 0.67. Analysis reveals that the Verifier incorrectly rejects two valid test implementations because it hallucinates a requirement not present in the specification (expecting assertion messages to match specific strings). The Executor then modifies its working solution to satisfy the Verifier's false requirement, introducing failures. This pattern, which we term \emph{verifier hallucination}, explains the negative average verification value ($-$5.8\%) observed across the benchmark and motivates future work on calibrated verification.
-
