-\section{Communication Analysis}
-\label{app:communication}
-
-We analyze planner-to-executor communication across 196 valid full-condition runs. Planner message volume shows no statistically significant correlation with task score ($r = 0.014$, $p = 0.848$, $n = 196$). Message count is similarly uncorrelated ($r = 0.068$, $p = 0.34$). Team-helping tasks exhibit higher active communication rates (86\% of runs with non-empty planner messages vs.\ 68\% for team-hurting tasks), but the difference is not significant at available sample sizes (Mann-Whitney $p = 0.29$). The dominant predictor of outcome is task type rather than communication volume: team-helping tasks outscore team-hurting tasks by 30 percentage points ($p = 0.0007$, $n = 33$). Notably, TEST2\_regression achieves 95\% partial score with only 579 characters of planner output, demonstrating that concise, targeted specification relay can be more effective than verbose plans.
-
-\section{TeamBench-Mini Representativeness}
-\label{app:mini-representativeness}
-
-TeamBench-Mini (28 tasks) covers 13 of 19 categories. The team uplift distribution of Mini does not significantly differ from the full benchmark (Kolmogorov-Smirnov $p = 0.572$), confirming that Mini preserves the core teamwork signal. However, Mini skews toward harder tasks: the mean oracle score is 0.375 (Mini) vs.\ 0.575 (Full), a significant difference (KS $p = 0.007$). Mini underrepresents adversarial (TRAP), cross-system (CROSS), cryptographic (CRYPTO), and distributed (DIST) categories. Cross-model findings on Mini should therefore be interpreted as reflecting performance on harder-than-average tasks; the team benefit observed on Mini (+8.0\% mean uplift) exceeds the full-benchmark average (+1.7\%), consistent with the equalizer effect concentrating team benefit on harder tasks.
-
-\section{Cost Analysis}
-\label{app:cost}
-
-Team coordination incurs approximately 4.7$\times$ the token cost of oracle runs (91K vs.\ 19K tokens per run). At Gemini 3 Flash pricing, the oracle achieves 183 score points per dollar while the full team achieves 47 score points per dollar, a 75\% reduction in cost efficiency. The team's +1.7\% aggregate score improvement does not justify the 4.7$\times$ cost increase for general use. However, for the hardest quintile (Q1), where team uplift reaches +15.3\%, the cost-adjusted benefit is positive: the team converts \$0.006/run into 0.27 average score versus the oracle's \$0.001/run for 0.12 average score, a 2.25$\times$ score improvement at 6$\times$ cost. The practical deployment guideline (Section~\ref{sec:implications}) reflects this asymmetry: deploy teams selectively on tasks where single agents fail, not uniformly.
-
-\section{Equalizer Mechanism Analysis}
-\label{app:equalizer-mechanism}
-
-We test three hypotheses for why weaker models benefit more from team coordination.
-
-\paragraph{H1: Specification relay.} If team benefit stems from the Planner relaying specification knowledge, tasks with larger necessity gaps (oracle $-$ restricted) should show greater team uplift. The opposite holds: necessity gap is significantly \emph{negatively} correlated with team uplift ($r = -0.446$, $p < 10^{-24}$, $n = 472$ task-model pairs), rejecting spec relay as the primary mechanism.
-
-\paragraph{H2: Step-limit exhaustion.} If single agents exhaust their step budget on hard tasks while teams distribute the budget across roles, oracle elapsed time should predict failure. Oracle elapsed time shows zero correlation with oracle score ($r = 0.00$, $p = 0.99$), and weak models fail equally fast regardless of task difficulty (hard/easy elapsed ratio = 0.93$\times$), ruling out budget exhaustion.
-
-\paragraph{H3: Implicit chain-of-thought.} If the planner's structured output functions as chain-of-thought reasoning for the executor, the no-plan condition should underperform the restricted condition on hard tasks. In fact, no-plan and restricted scores are statistically indistinguishable on hard tasks (mean diff = $-0.006$, $p = 0.66$, $n = 202$).
-
-\paragraph{Post-hoc finding: capability sweet-spot.} A quadratic model of team uplift vs.\ oracle score ($R^2 = 0.60$) substantially outperforms a linear model ($R^2 = 0.40$), with the vertex at oracle score 0.54. Mid-tier models benefit most (+7.6\%, $p = 0.002$); very weak models are harmed; very strong models see neutral effects. The ``equalizer'' label applies within the capable model range but not across the full capability spectrum.
-
-\section{Enhanced Oracle Baseline}
-\label{app:enhanced-oracle}
-
-Table~\ref{tab:enhanced-oracle} compares standard and enhanced oracle conditions against the full team on the 28-task TeamBench-Mini subset.
-
-\begin{table}[h]
-\centering
-\caption{Enhanced oracle baselines on TeamBench-Mini (28 tasks, Gemini 3 Flash). Structured prompting does not close the team gap; Oracle-CoT is worse than the standard oracle.}
-\label{tab:enhanced-oracle}
-\small
-\begin{tabular}{lcc}
-\toprule
-Condition & Avg.\ Partial Score & vs.\ Oracle \\
-\midrule
-Oracle (standard) & 0.704 & baseline \\
-Oracle-CoT & 0.640 & $-$6.4\% \\
-Oracle-2Pass & 0.698 & $-$0.6\% \\
-Full Team & \textbf{0.754} & $+$5.0\% \\
-\bottomrule
-\end{tabular}
-\end{table}
-
-The Oracle-CoT condition instructs the single agent to ``first read the full specification carefully, create a detailed plan, then implement the solution step by step.'' The Oracle-2Pass condition runs the agent in two sequential phases: a read-only specification comprehension phase followed by an implementation phase. Neither condition improves over the minimal oracle prompt, confirming that the team benefit derives from structural role separation (the Planner \emph{cannot} execute code; the Executor \emph{cannot} read the spec) rather than from implicit planning that a single agent could replicate with better instructions.
-
